sion was released.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Unreal Championship 2: The Liandri Conflict]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence. A censored version was released.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Unreal Tournament III]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence. A censored version was released.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n|Banned because of sexual activity involving people who are, or appear to be, children under 18 years.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Vivisector: Beast Within]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Wolfenstein (2009 video game)|Wolfenstein]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence and Nazi references.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Wolfenstein 3D]]''\n|Originally banned because of Nazi references. The ban has been overturned in 2019 on grounds of social adequacy.\n|-\n|''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]] (PS3, Xbox 360, PC)''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|}\n\n==Greece==\n{{see also|Law 3037/2002}}\nNo known games have been banned in [[Greece]]. A law banning ''all'' electronic games in public places was passed in 2002, but eventually disregarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/2100-1040-956357.html|title=In Greece, use a GameBoy, go to jail|last1=Goodwins|first1=Rupert|date=2002-09-02|website=[[CNet]]|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714120441/http://news.cnet.com/2100-1040-956357.html|archive-date=2014-07-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/2238242.stm|title=Greeks fight computer game ban|date=2002-09-05|work=BBC News|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305234852/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/2238242.stm|archive-date=2014-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/greek-game-ban-overturned/125096|title=Greek game ban overturned|last1=Loney|first1=Matt|date=2002-10-11|website=ZDNet|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326002333/http://www.zdnet.com/news/greek-game-ban-overturned/125096|archive-date=2014-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==India==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[PUBG Mobile]]''\n|Temporarily banned because of extreme violence. The move came after a direction from the [[Gujarat]] and [[Jammu and kashmir]] state department seeking a ban on the game, as it was claimed to affect the minds of youths who tend to become violent and banned in <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/technology/news/story/pubg-mobile-makes-player-go-mad-admitted-to-hospital-under-serious-trauma-1427705-2019-01-10</ref>[[Jammu and kashmir]] because people of [[Jammu and kashmir]] is playing pubg for 10 days without resting and got sick get banned a 6-hour ban<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/now-pubg-banned-in-city/articleshow/68399514.cms|title=Now, PUBG banned in city|last=Mar 14|first=Ahmedabad Mirror {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=Ahmedabad Mirror|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15|last3=Ist|first3=06:16}}</ref> The game was banned in [[Gujarat]] In the cities of [[Ahmedabad]], [[Surat]], [[Vadodara]], [[Bhavnagar]] And [[Rajkot]] and [[Jammu and kashmir]], but only for the mobile version.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/tech/pubg-mobile-ban-you-will-get-arrested-for-playing-the-battle-royal-game-in-these-cities-in-india-2066153.html|title=PUBG Mobile Ban: You Will Get Arrested For Playing The Battle Royal Game in These Cities in India|website=News18|access-date=2019-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331171414/https://www.news18.com/news/tech/pubg-mobile-ban-you-will-get-arrested-for-playing-the-battle-royal-game-in-these-cities-in-india-2066153.html|archive-date=2019-03-31|url-status=live}}</ref> PC and console versions remained unaffected of ban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/578080/PLAYERUNKNOWNS_BATTLEGROUNDS/|title=PLAYERUNKNOWN'S BATTLEGROUNDS on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507085804/https://store.steampowered.com/app/578080/PLAYERUNKNOWNS_BATTLEGROUNDS/|archive-date=2019-05-07|url-status=live}}</ref> .<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n|-\n| ''[[Dungeon Hunter 5]]''\n| Banned because Of the High Graphic Violence It is banned in [[Dharmanagar]] and [[Panisagar]] and the [[Dungeon Hunter 5]] mobile version is banned .<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1255814-breves |title=Breves \u2013 Alertan por el riesgo de un videojuego |date=19 April 2010 |access-date=30 July 2018 |work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]] |language=Bengali |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730203250/https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1255814-breves |archive-date=2018-07-30 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5520973/years-later-argentina-bans-rape-video-game|title=Years Later, Argentina Bans Rape Video Game|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Brian|date=21 April 2010|website=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=30 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730234744/https://kotaku.com/5520973/years-later-argentina-bans-rape-video-game|archive-date=2018-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ludo]]\n|Banned because of the ludo is very very \u09aa\u099a\u09be the Ludo is very very \u09aa\u099a\u09be because unable to get a 6 easily ludo Is banned in all [[Tripura]]\n|}\n\n==Iran==\n{{Main|Censorship in Iran}}\nIran typically bans any game that contains violence, depicts cruelty, features strong sexual content, nudity, or portrays the Middle East negatively.\n''[[Battlefield 3]]'' was banned because it presented a fictional U.S. invasion on [[Tehran]]. Even before the ban, many retail stores were removing copies of the game from their shelves.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCwtm31oYnU70sTJKF8iltAfNHnA?docId=CNG.8af6b7bf5835350c0f276c56855993c1.201 | title=Iran bans US video game showing Tehran invasion | publisher=AFP | date=Nov 28, 2011 | access-date=2018-10-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225212856/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCwtm31oYnU70sTJKF8iltAfNHnA?docId=CNG.8af6b7bf5835350c0f276c56855993c1.201 | archive-date=2012-02-25 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'' was banned due to security reasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pokemon Go banned by Iranian authorities over 'security'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-36989526|website=[[BBC]]|accessdate=2016-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917044204/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-36989526|archive-date=2016-09-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]'' was banned for excessively glorifying homosexual and immoral values. The ban does not extend to digital distribution, however.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=ir|title=VALKYRIE DRIVE -BHIKKHUNI- on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017224315/https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=ir|archive-date=2018-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Republic of Ireland==\n{{main|Video gaming in the Republic of Ireland}}\n\nThe [[Irish Film Classification Office|IFCO]] rarely rates video games, and leaves decisions to [[Pan European Game Information|PEGI]] and the [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]]. ''[[Manhunt 2]]'' was banned for \"gross, unrelenting, and gratuitous violence\", but the ban was later lifted and the game was given a PEGI 18 rating.<ref>[http://www.ifco.ie/ifco/ifcoweb.nsf/web/news?opendocument&news=yes&type=graphic \"Manhunt 2 Video Game Prohibited.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071120192726/http://www.ifco.ie/ifco/ifcoweb.nsf/web/news?opendocument&news=yes&type=graphic |date=2007-11-20 }} Irish Film Classification Office.</ref>\n\n==Italy==\nIn 2006, following the release of the trailer to the game ''[[Rule of Rose]]'', the magazine ''[[Panorama (magazine)|Panorama]]'' ran an article claiming live burials of children at the protagonist's hand. Shortly after, then-mayor of [[Rome]], [[Walter Veltroni]], called for a ban of the game in Italy. The game's European publisher, [[505 Games]], dismissed these claims,<ref name=\"Rule\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news171106ruleofrose|title=505 Games responds to Rule of Rose controversy|author=GamesIndustry International|date=November 17, 2006|publisher=Eurogamer.net|access-date=June 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625050518/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news171106ruleofrose|archive-date=2018-06-25|url-status=live}}</ref> and the game was not banned following Veltroni's comments.\n\nIn 2007, following the decision of the governments of the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], the Minister of Communications [[Paolo Gentiloni]] publicly expressed the desire to ban the distribution of ''[[Manhunt 2]]'' in Italy, due to the gratuitous violence and excessive cruelty in the video game, but the ban was never put into practice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://punto-informatico.it/2024293/PI/News/censura-gentiloni-blocca-manhunt.aspx |title=Censura, Gentiloni blocca Manhunt 2 |last1=Maruccia |first1=Alfonso |language=Italian |date=22 June 2007 |publisher=[[Punto Informatico]] |accessdate=11 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111235414/http://punto-informatico.it/2024293/PI/News/censura-gentiloni-blocca-manhunt.aspx |archive-date=2013-11-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Japan==\n{{main|\nVideo games in Japan}}\n\nVideo games are rarely banned in Japan, and it holds the place as one of the top video game producers in the world.<ref>[http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/features/arts/20081017TDY12001.htm \"Game over? Not yet: Japan's video game industry appears vibrant despite a crisis of confidence\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019122741/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/features/arts/20081017TDY12001.htm |date=2008-10-19 }} Daily Yomiuri Online.</ref> However, ''[[Fallout 3]]'' was edited in Japan due to two reasons: a quest named \"The Power of the Atom\" which gave the player a choice to nuke a city named Megaton, which caused part of the quest to be removed, and a weapon in the game called the [[Fat Man]]. Because of its relation to the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|real historic event]], the weapon was renamed to the Nuka Launcher in the Japanese version of ''Fallout 3''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://games.uk.msn.com/gaming/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=155028519&page=2 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606014629/http://games.uk.msn.com/gaming/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=155028519&page=2 |archive-date=2013-06-06 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> Japan's [[Spike (company)|Spike]] removed all references to [[Kim Jong-il]] and [[North Korea]] in ''[[Homefront (video game)|Homefront]]'', as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Laura |url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/action/homefront/news.html?sid=6297959 |title=Kim Jong-il axed from Homefront in Japan |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=2011-03-15 |accessdate=2011-10-26}}</ref> ''[[Resident Evil 4]]'', ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops]]'', ''[[Bulletstorm]]'', ''[[Gears of War 3]]'', ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'', ''[[Dead Island]]'', ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'' and numerous other violent titles{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}, distributed physically and digitally, were heavily edited for excessive violence, but only on the localization level; the games can still be played if the locale is switched from Japanese to English. The ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'' series was subsequently banned in Japan, including its newest release, due to heavy amounts of violence {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}. On March 13, 2019, the sales of ''[[Judgement (video game)|Judgement]]'' had stopped producing future sales in Japan, following [[Pierre Taki]]'s arrest on suspicion of cocaine use. As a result, [[Sega]] had replaced both the voice actor and the character model having been subsequently removed.\n\n==Kenya==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n|Banned because of sexual content and glorification of homosexuality. The ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=ke|title=VALKYRIE DRIVE -BHIKKHUNI- on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Malaysia==\n{{main|Video gaming in Malaysia}}\nMalaysia tends to ban offensive content such as extreme impact violence, depictions of cruelty, any content considered [[Criticism of Islam|anti-Muslim]], sexual content and nudity. In August 2008, after the ''Grand Theft Auto'' series ban in Thailand ([[List of banned video games#Thailand|see below]]), head of a Malaysian consumer rights organization, Muhammad Idris, called for the ban of the entire [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]] and other similarly violent video games such as the [[Manhunt (video game series)|''Manhunt'' series]] and ''[[Mortal Kombat]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.malaysianbar.org.my/legal/general_news/fomca_regulate_video_games.html |title=Fomca: Regulate video games |publisher=Malaysianbar.org.my |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2011-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610205540/http://www.malaysianbar.org.my/legal/general_news/fomca_regulate_video_games.html |archive-date=2011-06-10 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/malaysian-consumer-group-blame-it-all-on-gta-98824.phtml|title=Malaysian Consumer Group blame it all on GTA|last=Bennett|first=Colette|website=Destructoid|access-date=2010-01-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211200420/http://www.destructoid.com/malaysian-consumer-group-blame-it-all-on-gta-98824.phtml|archive-date=2010-02-11|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2010, one week after ''[[Dante's Inferno (video game)|Dante's Inferno]]'' was released, the game was banned by Jabatan Agama Islam (JAIS) in Malaysia for offensive depictions of cruelty, hellish visions, sexuality and content that was against [[Sharia]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nIn 2016, ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'' was banned by the Federal Territory for Muslims for promoting the search for power, which leads to gambling and safety issues related to playing the game. The ban was later lifted following massive backlash on social media and an update that slightly modified security measures on the app.\n\nIn September 2017, the [[Malaysian Communications and Multimedia Commission]] (MCMC) blocked access to the entire Steam store following the discovery of a controversial fighting game involving religious deities, Fight of Gods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140309/fighting-game-featuring-jesus-buddha-receives-condemnation-religious-leaders/|title=MCMC Blocks Entire Steam Store Following God Fighting Game Controversy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028152423/https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140309/fighting-game-featuring-jesus-buddha-receives-condemnation-religious-leaders/|archive-date=2017-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was lifted one day later after Valve agreed to block the game in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140631/mcmc-unblocks-steam-offending-game-geoblocked/|title=MCMC Unblocks Steam After Offending Game Geoblocked|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108215740/https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140631/mcmc-unblocks-steam-offending-game-geoblocked/|archive-date=2017-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Mexico==\nThough no video games have ever been banned in the country, ''[[Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Advanced Warfighter 2]]'' was banned in the state of [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] due to Mexican rebels being depicted as antagonists and stereotyping the cities of [[Chihuahua City]] and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]].<ref name=\"MEX-GRAW2\">{{cite web|last=Gaudiosi|first=John|work=WRAL News|date=2007-03-26|title=Locally-made \"GRAW2\" Banned in Mexico|url=http://www.wral.com/entertainment/blogpost/1248223/|publisher=wral.com|accessdate=2007-03-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070329014914/http://www.wral.com/entertainment/blogpost/1248223/|archivedate=2007-03-29}}</ref> However, the game can still be found in shelves in other states.\n\n==Nepal==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[PUBG]]''\n|Banned because of delinquency issues involving youths.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/12/18308618/pubg-ban-nepal-violence-video-game-addiction |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415004118/https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/12/18308618/pubg-ban-nepal-violence-video-game-addiction |archive-date=2019-04-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> At present, the ban has been lifted<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/578080/PLAYERUNKNOWNS_BATTLEGROUNDS/?cc=np|title=PLAYERUNKNOWN'S BATTLEGROUNDS on Steam|last=|first=|date=|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==New Zealand==\n{{main|Video gaming in New Zealand}}\nIn [[New Zealand]], games are classified by the [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (New Zealand)|country's Office of Film and Literature Classification]]. If they are dubbed \"objectionable\" in all cases, they are banned. In this case, the game in question is not only illegal to sell, but also to own, possess, or import. Games are typically banned and classified as \"objectionable content\" when they contain extreme violence, offensive depictions of cruelty, animal cruelty, sexual content involving children, or graphic depictions of sexual content, including sexual fetishes that are \"offensive & abhorrent\" (depictions of urination, [[bestiality]], [[necrophilia]], [[urophilia]], [[coprophilia]], and/or [[incest]]).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Criminal Girls: Invite Only]]''\n|Banned because of sexual content that focuses on young persons and elements of sexual violence.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.classificationoffice.govt.nz/news/classification-decision-snapshots |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127191516/https://www.classificationoffice.govt.nz/news/classification-decision-snapshots |archive-date=2018-01-27 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Gal*Gun: Double Peace]]''\n| Banned because \"it tends to promote and support both the exploitation of children and young people, and the use of [[coercion]] to compel a person to submit to sexual conduct\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fvlb.org.nz/nz/pages/publication-details.html?title=199675 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131190923/http://www.fvlb.org.nz/nz/pages/publication-details.html?title=199675 |archive-date=2017-01-31 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Manhunt (video game)|Manhunt]]''\n| Banned because of graphic violence and depictions of cruelty.<ref>[http://www.censorship.govt.nz/PDFWORD/manhunt.pdf Manhunt: Reasons for Decision] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203011642/http://www.censorship.govt.nz/PDFWORD/manhunt.pdf |date=February 3, 2007 }}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Manhunt 2]]''\n|Banned because of graphic violence and depictions of cruelty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nzgamer.com/news/2660/manhunt-2-banned-in-nz.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-06-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123091531/http://nzgamer.com/news/2660/manhunt-2-banned-in-nz.html |archive-date=2016-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Postal 2]]'' \n| Banned because of \"Gross, abhorrent content: Urination, High Impact Violence, Animal Cruelty, Homophobia, Racial, and Ethnic Stereotypes\u201d.<ref>''[https://www.geek.com/games/11-video-games-that-got-banned-and-why-1645406/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127045508/https://www.geek.com/games/11-video-games-that-got-banned-and-why-1645406/ |date=27 January 2019 }}'' By K. Thor Jensen 08.11.2018 :: 2:00PM EST kthorjensen.</ref>\n|-\n|-\n|''[[RapeLay]]''\n|Banned because it \"tends to promote and support the use of violence to compel a person to submit to sexual conduct, and the exploitation of young persons for sexual purposes\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n|-\n| ''[[Reservoir Dogs (video game)|Reservoir Dogs]]''\n| Banned because it \"tends to promote and support the infliction of extreme violence and extreme cruelty for the purpose of entertainment\".<ref>{{cite press release|title=Reservoir Dogs Computer Game Banned|publisher=New Zealand Office of Film and Literature Classification|date=2006-07-07|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO0607/S00059.htm|accessdate=2006-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716092216/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO0607/S00059.htm|archive-date=2006-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Three Sisters' Story]]''\n| Banned because it \"tends to promote and support the use of violence to compel a person to submit to sexual conduct, and the exploitation of young persons for sexual purposes\".{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n|-\n| ''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n| Banned because it \"tends to promote and support incest between the two lead focal sisters, and the exploitation of young persons for sexual purposes\".{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|}\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games is banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\n==North Korea==\nNorth Korea bans all foreign video games (regardless of content) and very few games are known to be developed in North Korea.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]''\n|Banned because of the presence of gambling in GTA Online. Gambling of any kind is banned in North Korea.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|[[Homefront (video game)|''Homefront'']]\n|Banned because of its negative portrayal of a unified Korea under Northern rule.<ref name=\"ZDNet Korea\"/>\n|}\n\n==Pakistan==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason \n|-\n|''[[Medal of Honor: Warfighter]]''\n\n| Banned for portraying Pakistanis negatively.<ref name=\"COD&MOH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/black-ops-2-warfighter-banned-in-pakistan-for-depicting-country/|title=Black Ops 2, Warfighter banned in Pakistan for depicting country in 'very poor light'|date=2013-01-23|website=Joystiq|last1=Conditt|first1=Jessica|accessdate=2014-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126101228/http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/black-ops-2-warfighter-banned-in-pakistan-for-depicting-country|archive-date=2013-01-26|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/202970/Call_of_Duty_Black_Ops_II/?cc=pk|title=Call of Duty\u00ae: Black Ops II on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Postal 2]]''\n| Banned because of violence against Muslims who are portrayed as terrorists. The ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n|-\n| ''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n| Banned because of sexual content and glorifying homosexuality. However, the ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=pk|title=VALKYRIE DRIVE -BHIKKHUNI- on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020214004/https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=pk|archive-date=2018-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[https://g.co/kgs/p4xexy Negligee: Love Stories]\n|Banned for sexual content and glorifying homosexuality.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} The ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/1002100/Negligee_Love_Stories/?cc=pk|title=Negligee: Love Stories on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Philippines==\n{{main|Video gaming in the Philippines}}\nIn 1981, a presidential decree issued by [[Ferdinand Marcos]] outlawed the use and distribution<ref name=\"Long\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/11/1119marcos-bans-videogames-philippines/|title=Nov. 19, 1981: Marcos Regime Puts the Kibosh on Games|last=Long|first=Tony|date=19 November 2010|work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|accessdate=26 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226052812/http://www.wired.com/2010/11/1119marcos-bans-videogames-philippines/|archive-date=2015-02-26|url-status=live}}</ref> of ''all'' video game consoles, arcade games and pinball machines, deeming them as a \"destructive social enemy\"<ref>{{cite news|title=President Marcos bans video game machines|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/10056192/?terms=marcos+video+games|newspaper=Logansport Pharos-Tribune|date=19 November 1981|page=17|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate=February 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320055905/http://www.newspapers.com/image/10056192/?terms=marcos+video+games|archive-date=2015-03-20|url-status=live}} {{Open access}}</ref> and \"to the detriment of the public interest\".<ref name=\"PD519\">{{cite web|url=http://source.gosupra.com/docs/provision/78753|title=Presidential Decree No. 519 - Supra Source|accessdate=26 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107151855/http://source.gosupra.com/docs/provision/78753|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Dillon|first=Roberto|title=The Golden Age of Video Games: The Birth of a Multibillion Dollar Industry|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1439873232|date=12 April 2011|publisher=CRC Press|location=Page xvii|isbn=978-1439873236}}</ref> Despite the law being technically in effect following the [[EDSA Revolution]], it has since been disregarded and unenforced.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nWhile no video games are banned nationwide so far since 1986, at least one title, ''[[Defense of the Ancients]]'', has been banned at a [[barangay]] in [[Dasmari\u00f1as, Cavite]] following complaints of [[Juvenile delinquency|delinquency]] issues, and two murder incidents involving youths in the area resulting from brawls in relation to the game.<ref name=\"DOTABan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/413042/news/regions/dota-banned-in-internet-shops-in-cavite-village|title=DOTA banned in internet shops in Cavite village|date=21 January 2015|work=[[GMA News]]|accessdate=27 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065934/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/413042/news/regions/dota-banned-in-internet-shops-in-cavite-village|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Russia==\nIn [[Russia]], games are classified by the \"[[On Protecting Children from Information Harmful to Their Health and Development]]\" federal law. No known games have been banned in Russia due to excessive violence, nudity, negative portrayal of people of Russia or expression of religious views of any kind because of the freedom of speech guaranteed by the [[Constitution of Russia]]. Media in the [[United States]] and [[Europe]] have incorrectly reported that ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2]]'', which features a storyline in which Russian \"[[ultranationalists]]\" take control of the country and invade the United States, was banned in Russia. Activision called these reports 'erroneous'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/6588218/Call-Of-Duty-Modern-Warfare-2-not-banned-in-Russia-says-Activision.html|title=Call Of Duty: Modern Warfare 2 not banned in Russia, says Activision|last=Cowen|first=Nick|date=2009-11-17|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=21 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020080012/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/6588218/Call-Of-Duty-Modern-Warfare-2-not-banned-in-Russia-says-Activision.html|archive-date=2010-10-20|location=London|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Sony Interactive Entertainment Russia refused to sell ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare (2019 video game)|Call of Duty: Modern Warfare]]'' digitally.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n| ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare (2019 video game)|Call of Duty: Modern Warfare]]''\n| Not officially banned, but Sony Interactive Entertainment refused to sell the game digitally on PlayStation 4.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dexerto.com/call-of-duty/call-of-duty-modern-warfare-banned-russian-playstation-store-1171401 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-10-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022182738/https://www.dexerto.com/call-of-duty/call-of-duty-modern-warfare-banned-russian-playstation-store-1171401 |archive-date=2019-10-22 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Saudi Arabia==\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games is banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\nMost of these games can be found in some stores (often at a substantial price) due to the government failing to enforce the bans of these games. However, many major stores will not stock the following banned titles.<ref>http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616030323/http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx |date=2018-06-16 }} (Only Arabic Texture)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616030323/http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx |archive-date=2018-06-16 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Name\n!Reason\n|-\n|''[[God of War (franchise)]]''\n| Banned for a few weeks due to the presence of interactive sex scenes, partial nudity, and sexual themes, as well as the word \"God\" in the title. In 2018, the newest game in the series was approved for release.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Call of Duty 4: Modern Warfare]]''\n|Banned for a few weeks because of role-playing the Middle East as terrorists.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Assassin's Creed]]''\n|Banned for two weeks because of a perceived negative portrayal of Arabs. Later completely banned due to its use in the Blue Whale Challenge.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n|-\n|''[[Grand Theft Auto (series)]]''\n|Banned for extreme impact violence and nudity.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Heavy Rain]]''\n|Banned because of high impact violence, nudity, and a sex scene.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[L.A. Noire]]''\n|Banned because of extreme impact violence and nudity.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Postal 2]]''\n|Banned because of extreme impact violence, nudity and the portrayal of Muslims as terrorists.\n|-\n|''[[Red Dead Redemption]]''\n|Banned due to nudity, prostitution, violence, and cruelty.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Red Dead Redemption 2]]''\n|Banned due to nudity, prostitution, violence, and cruelty.\n|-\n|''[[Manhunt (video game series)]]'' (all versions)\n|Banned because of low impact scary violence and cruelty.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|- \n|''[[Manhunt 2]]''\n|Banned for \"gross, unrelenting, and gratuitous violence\".{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[South Park: The Stick of Truth]]/[[South Park: The Fractured but Whole|The Fractured but Whole]]'' (all versions)\n| Banned because of extremely offensive content.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]'' \n| Banned due to sexual content and excessive themes of glorifying homosexuality.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n|-\n|''[[Wolfenstein (series)|Wolfenstein]]'' \n| Banned because of the presence of interactive sex scenes.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n|-\n|''[[Metro (series)]]'' \n| Banned due to its use in the Blue Whale Challenge.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n|-\n|''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]''\n|Banned because of the presence of sex scenes.\n|-\n|''[[Watch Dogs (series)]]''\n|Banned due to frequent use of sexual expletives, sexual activity with visible genitals and the motiveless killing of innocent human characters.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n\n==Singapore==\n[[Singapore]] rarely bans games. With the implementation of the Video Game Classification in 2008 by the [[Media Development Authority]], most games are widely available for purchase to their respective age group, such as those containing full frontal nudity or strong graphic violence under an \"M18\" rating. Games that were previously banned such as [[Mass Effect]] were re-rated either \"Age Advisory\" or \"M18\" after the implementation of the classification system.\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Name\n!Reason\n|-\n|''[[Half-Life (video game)|Half-Life]]''\n|Banned because of violence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore Bans Half-Life|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/singapore-bans-half-life/1100-2446255/|publisher=Gamespot|date=24 January 2000|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160523174058/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/singapore-bans-half-life/1100-2446255/|archive-date=2016-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref>  The ban was met with uproar as the local gaming community and retailers scrambled to start petitions to save the game. The government decided to lift the ban after a week, as the game had been released for more than a year and the ban would impact the local LAN gaming and retail market.<ref>{{cite web|title=Half-Life ban lifted|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/half-life-ban-lifted/1100-2446436/|publisher=Gamespot|date=3 February 2000|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107151856/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/half-life-ban-lifted/1100-2446436/|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Mass Effect]]''\n|Banned because of a homosexual encounter between a feminine alien and female human.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory?id=3872709 \"Singapore Bans Game Over Lesbian Scene.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226002102/http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory?id=3872709 |date=2009-02-26 }} ABC News.</ref> The ban was later lifted and the title re-rated M18.<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10476791\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/location/story.cfm?l_id=3&objectid=10476791 |title=Ban lifted on Xbox game with sex scene |date=November 18, 2007 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=October 14, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Darkness (video game)|The Darkness]]''\n|Banned because of excessive violence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameaxis.com/home/?blog=1558 |title=The Darkness - Banned in Singapore (Game Axis) |access-date=2007-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215001649/http://www.gameaxis.com/home/?blog=1558 |archive-date=2007-12-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ban was later lifted and the title re-rated M18.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n|}\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games is banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\n==South Korea==\n{{see also|Video gaming in South Korea}}\nSince 2006, South Korea offers complete freedom in publishing games, fully respecting freedom of expression and speech. Even before this, games were very rarely banned unless that game mentioned elements of the [[Korean War]] in order to avoid tensions between the [[North Korea]] and [[South Korea]]. However, ''[[Manhunt (video game)|Manhunt]]'', ''[[Manhunt 2]]'', and ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' are still banned because of violence and cruelty. ''[[Grand Theft Auto III]]'', ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City]]'' and ''[[Mercenaries: Playground of Destruction]]'' were previously banned, but the bans were later lifted.<ref>''[http://www.gamespot.com/news/6163609.html Korea lifts game censorship] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070827022848/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6163609.html |date=2007-08-27 }}'' by Emma Boyes, 2006-12-29, [[GameSpot]]</ref>\n\nThe [[Game Rating Board]] requires that all video games be rated by the organization. Unrated titles are absolutely banned from being sold in the country, and websites selling them can be blocked.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|''Mortal Kombat'' (2011)]]\n|Banned because of excessive violence and cruelty.<ref name=\"ZDNet Korea\">{{cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.co.kr/news/news_view.asp?artice_id=20110407102001|script-title=ko:\uc131\uc778 \uac8c\uc784 \ubaa8\ud0c8\ucef4\ubc43, \uc2ec\uc758 '\uac70\ubd80'\u2026\uc5ed\uc2dc \uc794\uc778\ud574\uc11c?|date=2011-04-07|work=[[ZDNet|ZDNet Korea]]|language=ja|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060034/http://www.zdnet.co.kr/news/news_view.asp?artice_id=20110407102001|archive-date=2013-10-23|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Homefront (video game)|''Homefront'']]\n|Banned because of its negative portrayal of a unified Korea under Northern rule.<ref name=\"ZDNet Korea\"/>\n|-\n|[[Danganronpa V3: Killing Harmony|''Danganronpa V3'']]\n|The September 2017 release was cancelled because of a <!-- how recent? -->case in South Korea where a 17-year-old girl killed and dismembered an 8-year-old child.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} The game was banned to prevent controversies.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n|}\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games was banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\n==Thailand==\n[[Thailand]] will typically ban any games with excessive violence, and sexual content, such as many [[eroge]] from Japan, for the same reasons as its ban on any pornographic films.\n\nAdditionally, since August 2008, all video game titles of the ''[[Grand Theft Auto]]'' series have been completely banned in Thailand,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thainn.com/exchange/temp_news.php?type1=1&type2=4&page=0&topic=5346&view=0 |title=\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e41\u0e1a\u0e19GTA \u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e40\u0e01\u0e21\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e21\u0e35\u0e42\u0e14\u0e19\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a |accessdate=2009-08-09 |date=2008-08-06 |work=[[Daily News (Thailand)|Daily News]] |publisher=ThaiNN.com |language=th |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817095730/http://www.thainn.com/exchange/temp_news.php?type1=1&type2=4&page=0&topic=5346&view=0 |archive-date=2008-08-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> because of a case where an 18-year-old Thai player supposedly influenced by ''Grand Theft Auto'' killed a taxi driver from Bangkok.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sanook.com/crime/crime_293428.php? |title=\u0e2a\u0e25\u0e14! \u0e21.6 \u0e41\u0e17\u0e07\u0e42\u0e2b\u0e14\u0e06\u0e48\u0e32\u0e41\u0e17\u0e47\u0e01\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e40\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e19\u0e41\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e01\u0e21\u0e42\u0e08\u0e23 GTA |accessdate=2009-08-09 |date=2008-08-04 |work=[[Thai Rath]] |publisher=Sanook.com |language=th |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331191217/http://news.sanook.com/crime/crime_293428.php |archive-date=2009-03-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe ban, however, does not extend to the digital PC versions of [[Grand Theft Auto V]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/271590/Grand_Theft_Auto_V/?cc=th|title=Grand Theft Auto V on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302090814/https://store.steampowered.com/app/271590/Grand_Theft_Auto_V/?cc=th|archive-date=2019-03-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Tropico 5]] is yet another banned title. The military junta claims that it could \"affect peace and order\" within the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tropico-5-banned-in-thailand-because-it-could-affe/1100-6421473/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801094320/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tropico-5-banned-in-thailand-because-it-could-affe/1100-6421473/ |archive-date=2018-08-01 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n==United Arab Emirates==\n<!--- TO DO: get sources for games with unknown reasons --->\nIn the [[United Arab Emirates]], a branch of the government called the [[National Media Council (United Arab Emirates)|National Media Council]] (NMC) works to control the media and entertainment industry in the country, and they have the authority to issue bans on any specific media products, including video games, to comply with the country's legal and cultural values. Usually, the NMC do not explicitly state their actual consensus for any kind of issued ban on a product, so official reasons behind their bans remain unclear. However, bans issued by the NMC apply only to the sale of those products through local outlets; they do not make private ownership illegal. There are certain exceptions, notably for ''[[Spec Ops: The Line]]'' (see below). Some banned games may be available and sold on the nation's [[grey market]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nIn 2018, the NMC introduced a localised rating system for various media, including video games.<ref name=\"NMCratings\">{{cite web |last=Salama |first=Samir |url=https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/media/new-uae-ratings-system-for-films-games-books-1.2176427 |title=New UAE ratings system for films, games, books |work=[[Gulf News]] |date=2018-02-20 |accessdate=2018-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521021047/https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/media/new-uae-ratings-system-for-films-games-books-1.2176427 |archive-date=2018-05-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe following <!-- incomplete list --> titles are banned from mainstream physical retail.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n| ''[[BlazBlue: Continuum Shift]]''\n| Banned likely due to suggestive and revealing outfits on some characters.<ref>{{cite web\n |publisher    = gamesradar\n |url          = http://www.gamesradar.com/blazblue-continuum-shift-banned-in-united-arab-emirates/\n |title        = BlazBlue: Continuum Shift banned in United Arab Emirates\n |last       = Nagata\n |first       = Tyler\n |date         = February 1, 2011\n |accessdate   = 2012-08-06\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20151009084303/http://www.gamesradar.com/blazblue-continuum-shift-banned-in-united-arab-emirates/\n |archive-date = 2015-10-09\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to digital versions of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2]]''\n| This game was banned after players in the GCC noticed that the picture frames in some maps had quotations from the Qur'an, which were very offensive to Muslims.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} The ban was lifted after the developers removed the text on the frames.\n|-\n| ''[[Darksiders]]''\n| Banned likely due to contradicting with customs and traditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/37056/UAE-Darksiders-bannedrnrnUAE-Darksiders-bannedrn|title=UAE: Darksiders banned|access-date=2010-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113153445/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/37056/UAE-Darksiders-bannedrnrnUAE-Darksiders-bannedrn|archive-date=2010-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to the digital version of the game. Its sequel, ''[[Darksiders II]]'', which features similar themes, was released without issues, and even had a localised print release for the PlayStation 3 version.\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Island]]'' and ''[[Dead Island: Riptide]]''\n| Both banned likely due to \"extreme depictions of violence and scantily-clad game characters\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itp.net/586074-dead-island-banned-in-the-uae|title=Dead Island banned|access-date=2011-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910014706/http://www.itp.net/586074-dead-island-banned-in-the-uae|archive-date=2011-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to digital versions of the games.\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Rising 2]]''\n| Banned likely due to violence, gambling, and nudity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=491026752624&id=27495087624|title=Official Geekay Games (U.A.E.'s biggest video game retailer) Facebook page stating ''Dead Rising 2'' is banned in the U.A.E.|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602224339/https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=491026752624&id=27495087624|archive-date=2017-06-02|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban has since been lifted for newer prints of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Dragon Age: Origins]]''\n| Banned likely due to sexual themes, including possible homosexual relationships.<ref name=\"ME2&DA:O Banned\">{{cite web|url=http://tbreak.com/megamers/7311/news/mass-effect-2-now-banned-in-the-uae.html|title=Mass Effect 2 and Dragon Age: Origins now banned in the UAE|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811001919/http://tbreak.com/megamers/7311/news/mass-effect-2-now-banned-in-the-uae.html|archivedate=2010-08-11}}</ref> The ban has since been lifted for the digital versions of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]''\n| Banned likely due to gambling and sexual themes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=10150093681037625&id=27495087624|title=Official Geekay Games (U.A.E.'s biggest video game retailer) Facebook page stating ''Fallout: New Vegas'' is banned in the U.A.E.|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107151855/https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=10150093681037625&id=27495087624|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to the digital version of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Gal*Gun: Double Peace]]'', ''[[Gal*Gun 2]]''\n| Both banned likely due to sexual themes. However, the ban did not extend to the digital versions of the games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/511740/GalGun_Double_Peace/|title=Gal*Gun: Double Peace on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507104901/https://store.steampowered.com/app/511740/GalGun_Double_Peace/|archive-date=2019-05-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/851890/GalGun_2/|title=Gal*Gun 2 on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507104858/https://store.steampowered.com/app/851890/GalGun_2/|archive-date=2019-05-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Godfather II (video game)|The Godfather II]]''\n| Banned likely due to nudity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbreak.com/megamers/3868/news/the-godfather-ii-banned-in-the-uae.html|title=The Godfather II Banned in the UAE|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918052034/http://tbreak.com/megamers/3868/news/the-godfather-ii-banned-in-the-uae.html|archivedate=2010-09-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[God of War (franchise)|''God of War'' series]]\n| The first title in the series was banned after complaints were filed regarding religious and sexual content in the game, and subsequently, the next seven games in the series were banned for similar reasons. The 2018 title ''[[God of War (2018 video game)|God of War]]'' was the first entry to be legally approved for release in the U.A.E.<ref name=\"GOWreleaseAE\">{{cite web |last=Lau |first=Evelyn |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/god-of-war-approved-for-uae-release-1.722384 |title=God of War approved for UAE release |work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |date=2018-04-17 |accessdate=2018-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521104329/https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/god-of-war-approved-for-uae-release-1.722384 |archive-date=2018-05-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]]\n| Banned likely due to violence, cruelty and sexual content. For unknown reasons, ''[[Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas]]'' has been available via Steam ever since the PC version of ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'' was launched, which itself is openly available on Steam from the debut. Shortly after Steam introduced the [[United Arab Emirates dirham|dirham]] as the official currency for U.A.E. user accounts on November 10, 2015,<ref name=\"IGNcitesAEDSteam\">{{cite web |last=Fakhruddin |first=Mufaddal |url=http://me.ign.com/en/pc/112849/news/steam-to-show-prices-in-uae-dirhams |title=Steam to Show Prices in UAE Dirhams |publisher=IGN Middle East |date=2015-11-04 |accessdate=2016-04-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020214004/https://me.ign.com/en/pc/112849/news/steam-to-show-prices-in-uae-dirhams |archive-date=2018-10-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> the majority of [[Rockstar Games|Rockstar]]'s games became available for purchase for those user accounts, including most ''Grand Theft Auto'' titles (For unknown reasons, almost all of Rockstar's games were regionally locked out on Steam, whether banned or not.).\n|-\n| ''[[Heavy Rain]]''\n| Banned likely due to graphic violence, sexual content, nudity<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-bans-latest-playstation-3-game-66005.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718205336/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-bans-latest-playstation-3-game-66005.html |archive-date=2016-07-18 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> and a sultry seduction scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbreak.com/megamers/7280/news/heavy-rain-not-in-the-uae.html|title=Heavy Rain? Not in the UAE.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926150653/http://tbreak.com/megamers/7280/news/heavy-rain-not-in-the-uae.html|archivedate=2010-09-26}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Injustice: Gods Among Us]]''\n| Despite being initially marketed for Middle Eastern distribution under the title of ''Injustice: The Mighty Among Us'', the game failed to surpass the NMC's censors for a period of time,<ref name=\"IGAUinUAE\">{{cite web |last=Fakhruddin |first=Mufaddal |url=http://me.ign.com/en/news/10356/injustice-gods-among-us-banned-in-uae-kuwait |title=Injustice: Gods Among Us Banned in UAE, Kuwait |publisher=IGN Middle East |date=2013-04-29 |accessdate=2013-04-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501221816/http://me.ign.com/en/news/10356/injustice-gods-among-us-banned-in-uae-kuwait |archive-date=2013-05-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was banned likely due to the case package and on-disc software title itself being identical to its European release, with the term \"[[God in Islam|God]]\" retained (the official reason was not given). The game had been demonstrated at various events in the U.A.E. without incident for many months before the official release date. However, the ban on the title has since been lifted.<ref name=\"IGAUinUAE\" /> The expanded ''Ultimate Edition'' was released on schedule and distributed regularly.\n|-\n| ''[[Mafia II]]''\n| Banned likely due to excessive violence and nudity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/mafia-ii-video-game-banned-in-uae-348114.html|title=Mafia II video game banned in the UAE|access-date=2010-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121030331/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/mafia-ii-video-game-banned-in-uae-348114.html|archive-date=2011-11-21|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban has since been lifted for digital versions of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Mass Effect 2]]'', ''[[Mass Effect 3]]''\n| Both banned likely due to possible homosexual relationships.<ref name=\"ME2&DA:O Banned\" /> However, the ban did not extend to the digital versions of the games.\n|-\n| ''[[Max Payne 3]]''\n| Banned likely due to excessive violence and sexual themes.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fakhruddin |first=Mufaddal |url=http://me.ign.com/en/news/1595/Max-Payne-3-Banned-in-UAE |title=Max Payne 3 Banned in UAE |publisher=IGN Middle East |date=2012-06-14 |accessdate=2012-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617021235/http://me.ign.com/en/news/1595/Max-Payne-3-Banned-in-UAE |archive-date=2012-06-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ban was issued roughly three weeks after the official release. The ban has since been lifted for digital versions of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/204100/Max_Payne_3/?cc=ae|title=Max Payne 3 on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018122317/https://store.steampowered.com/app/204100/Max_Payne_3/?cc=ae|archive-date=2018-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Omega Labyrinth Z]]''\n| Banned likely due to excessive sexual themes. However, the ban did not extend to the digital version of the game.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n|-\n| ''[[Postal 2]]''\n| Banned likely due to violence against Muslims, as well as excessive violence, sexual themes and other highly questionable content. However, the ban did not extend to the digital version of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Red Dead Redemption]]''\n| Was initially banned,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://megamers.tbreak.com/8622/news/red-dead-redemption-banned.html|title=Red Dead Redemption Banned?|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520032927/http://megamers.tbreak.com/8622/news/red-dead-redemption-banned.html|archivedate=2010-05-20}}</ref> likely due to nudity. The ban was lifted two months after the official release date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=461869667624&id=27495087624|title=Official Geekay Games (U.A.E.'s biggest video game retailer) Facebook page stating ''Red Dead Redemption'' now unbanned in the U.A.E.|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107151855/https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=461869667624&id=27495087624|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/wild-west-video-game-bucks-trend|title=Wild West video game bucks trend|access-date=2010-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616074917/http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/wild-west-video-game-bucks-trend|archive-date=2013-06-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Roblox|ROBLOX]]''\n| Banned due to the game containing [[user-generated content]] that include swearing and sexually explicit material.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/uae-bans-gaming-website-popular-among-children-1.732121|title=UAE bans gaming website popular among children|work=The National|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615214549/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/uae-bans-gaming-website-popular-among-children-1.732121|archive-date=2018-06-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ROBLOX banned in United Arab Emirates|author=BYA Gamer|date=June 12, 2018|publisher=ROBLOX inc.|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/nation/dubai/youth-aghast-parents-elated-as-popular-online-game-is-banned-in-uae|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Saints Row: The Third]]'', ''[[Saints Row IV]]''\n| Both banned likely due to sexual themes, excessive violence, and use of drugs and alcohol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itp.net/587021-saints-row-the-third-banned-in-the-uae|title=Saints Row: The Third banned in the UAE|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616030526/http://www.itp.net/587021-saints-row-the-third-banned-in-the-uae|archive-date=2018-06-16|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to the digital versions of the games.\n|-\n| ''[[Spec Ops: The Line]]''\n| Banned likely due to the game's fictional depiction of the UAE's real-life city of [[Dubai]] in a state of ravage and destruction. Unlike other banned video games, the NMC had extended their focus for this title going far as to issue the [[Telecommunications Regulatory Authority (UAE)|TRA]] to block the game's official website<ref>{{cite news |last=Simpson |first=Colin Simpson |url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/spec-ops-game-preview-blocked-in-uae |title=Spec Ops game preview blocked in UAE |newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |date=2012-06-21 |accessdate=2012-07-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725031541/http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/spec-ops-game-preview-blocked-in-uae |archive-date=2012-07-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> and subsequently prevent the title from being distributed throughout the rest of the [[Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf|GCC]], as well as [[Jordan]], and [[Lebanon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://moeys.net/amman-jordan/spec-ops-the-line-banned-in-uae-and-the-region/ |title=Spec Ops: The Line - Banned in the UAE and the region |publisher=Moey's.net |date=2012-06-20 |accessdate=2012-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728060720/http://moeys.net/amman-jordan/spec-ops-the-line-banned-in-uae-and-the-region/ |archivedate=2012-07-28 }}</ref> Even local retailers, such as Geekay Games, are unable to sell the game via their online shops to UAE residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geekaygames.com/ps3/spec-ops-the-line.html|title=PlayStation 3 port of Spec Ops: The Line available via Geekay Games' online store, but notes is not for sale in the U.A.E. (Xbox 360 port is also included, and treated likewise.)|access-date=2012-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307183520/http://www.geekaygames.com/ps3/spec-ops-the-line.html|archive-date=2013-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> The game remains unavailable via digital platforms such as [[Steam (software)|Steam]] and [[PlayStation Network|PSN]].\n|-\n| ''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n| Banned likely due to homosexual relationships between characters and high-impact sexual themes. However, the ban did not extend to the digital version of the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/|title=VALKYRIE DRIVE -BHIKKHUNI- on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507104857/https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/|archive-date=2019-05-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n\n==United Kingdom==\n{{main|Video gaming in the United Kingdom}}\nGames in the UK usually only receive a ban when they contain real sex scenes and/or gratuitous violence. [[BBFC]] age ratings are compulsory and backed by legislation, taking effect on July 30, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukie.org.uk/content/pegi-ratings-become-uk%E2%80%99s-single-video-game-age-rating-system|title=PEGI ratings become UK's single video game age rating system|date=2012-07-30|publisher=[[The Association For UK Interactive Entertainment]]|accessdate=2012-12-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028222558/http://ukie.org.uk/content/pegi-ratings-become-uk%E2%80%99s-single-video-game-age-rating-system|archive-date=2012-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> It is illegal to sell, buy or rent, but not import, a game that has not been classified by an approved age rating organisation in the UK. This only applies to games stored on [[Data storage device|physical media]], not downloadable media.<ref>[http://www.mcvuk.com/index.php/news/read/the-digital-download-bbfc-loophole/0190 The Digital Download BBFC Loophole] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307034453/http://www.mcvuk.com/index.php/news/read/the-digital-download-bbfc-loophole/0190 |date=2016-03-07 }} by Phil Lee & Ray Coyle, 2007-11-28, (MCV)</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Name\n!Reason\n|-\n|''[[Carmageddon]]''\n|Was threatened with being refused certification in its uncut form. Was subsequently altered to replace pedestrians with zombies.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/banned--but-still-on-the-road-1246147.html \"Banned But Still On The Road\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629122600/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/banned--but-still-on-the-road-1246147.html |date=2015-06-29 }} The Independent.</ref> The restriction was later lifted, and a patch was released to restore the original human content.\n|-\n|''[[Manhunt 2]]''\n|The uncut version was the only game to be refused classification by the [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]] (therefore banned), due to excessive graphic violence and cruelty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.next-gen.biz/news/uk-manhunt-2-banned-rockstar-responds |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120909234146/http://www.next-gen.biz/news/uk-manhunt-2-banned-rockstar-responds |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-09 |title=UK: Manhunt 2 Banned, Rockstar Responds - Edge Magazine |publisher=Next-gen.biz |date=2007-06-19 |accessdate=2011-10-26 }}</ref> After this, a modified version was made and submitted for certification \u2013 this was initially refused classification as well, but was allowed to be sold after an appeal (despite a successful challenge to this ruling).\n|-\n|''[[The Punisher (2005 video game)|The Punisher]]''\n|The version of the game that had been edited for the American market was further censored for the British release. The interrogation scenes were deemed graphically controversial and edits were made at the request of the BBFC to further mask these scenes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/case-studies/punisher |title=Case Study: The Punisher |publisher=bbfc.co.uk |accessdate=2014-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112190912/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/case-studies/punisher |archive-date=2014-11-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> The edited version received an [[18 (British Board of Film Classification)|18 certificate]].\n|}\n\n==United States==\n{{main|Video gaming in the United States}}\n\nIn the United States, the [[Entertainment Software Rating Board]] (ESRB)\u2014a [[Industry self-regulation|self-regulatory]] organization, issues ratings for video games and enforces voluntary regulations on how they are marketed and sold.<ref name=\"ars-ftcratings\">{{cite web | url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2008/05/ftc-report-retailers-clamping-down-on-m-rated-game-sales/ | title=FTC report: retailers clamping down on M-rated game sales | publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications | work=Ars Technica | accessdate=November 22, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202224255/http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2008/05/ftc-report-retailers-clamping-down-on-m-rated-game-sales/ | archive-date=2013-12-02 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Brown v. Entertainment Merchants Association]]''\u2014which challenged a California law restricting the sale of \"violent video games\" (defined using a variation of the [[Miller test]] separate from ratings assigned by bodies such as the ESRB) to minors, insisting that video games were considered a [[Freedom of speech in the United States|protected form of expression]] under the [[First Amendment]], meaning that federal or state law cannot be used to regulate their distribution based on content.<ref name=\"gamasutra analysis\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/6191/video_game_regulation_and_the_.php | title = Video Game Regulation and the Supreme Court: Schwarzenegger v. Entertainment Merchants Association | first = S. Gregory | last = Boyd | date = November 1, 2010 | accessdate = November 1, 2010 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | publisher = UBM plc | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101102225129/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/6191/video_game_regulation_and_the_.php | archive-date = 2010-11-02 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\"wired-california\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2011/06/violent-video-games-scotus/ | title=States May Not Ban Sale, Rental of Violent Videogames to Minors | publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications | work=Wired | accessdate=December 16, 2013 | first=David | last=Kravets | date=June 27, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629093204/http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2011/06/violent-video-games-scotus/ | archive-date=2011-06-29 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHowever, games can still be [[product recall|recalled]] as the result of court orders; a nude model featured in ''[[The Guy Game]]'' sued its developer and publisher over use of her likeness, as she was underage at the time of filming and thus could not personally consent to her depiction. All remaining copies of the game that contained her likeness were recalled from stores.<ref name=\"cnet-guygamelawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Topless teen sues over 'The Guy Game'|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/topless-teen-sues-over-the-guy-game/|website=CNET|accessdate=31 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825014315/http://www.cnet.com/news/topless-teen-sues-over-the-guy-game/|archive-date=2016-08-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"gamespot-guygamebanned\">{{cite web|title=The Guy Game banned, goes straight to video|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-guy-game-banned-goes-straight-to-video/1100-6128746/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=31 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905225527/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-guy-game-banned-goes-straight-to-video/1100-6128746/|archive-date=2016-09-05|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, a court found that [[Silicon Knights]] had plagiarized [[Epic Games]]' proprietary [[Unreal Engine|Unreal]] [[video game engine|engine]], and had used it in ''[[Too Human]]'' and ''[[X-Men: Destiny]]'', along with other unreleased projects. The studio was ordered to recall and destroy all remaining copies, materials, and source code relating to the games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2012/11/09/epic-judgment-doubled-silicon-knights-ordered-to-pay-over-9-million/|title=Epic judgment doubled, Silicon Knights ordered to pay over $9 million. Silicon Knights were ordered to pay $4.45 Million in damages to Epic Games.|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726010311/https://www.vg247.com/2012/11/09/epic-judgment-doubled-silicon-knights-ordered-to-pay-over-9-million/|archive-date=2018-07-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://docs.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/north-carolina/ncedce/5:2007cv00275/89570/862/ |title=Silicon Knights, Inc. v. Epic Games, Inc. Filing: 862 |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829100904/https://docs.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/north-carolina/ncedce/5:2007cv00275/89570/862 |archive-date=2018-08-29 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe ESRB's highest rating, \"[[List of AO-rated video games|Adults Only]]\", has been considered a total ban on the mainstream sale of certain games, as most retailers refuse to stock games carrying the rating, and they cannot be published on major video game consoles due to company policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/168266/We_could_use_more_Adults_Only_games_says_ESRBs_Vance.php|title=We could use more 'Adults Only' games, says ESRB's Vance|date=April 10, 2012|work=[[Gamasutra]]|accessdate=September 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111122310/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/168266/We_could_use_more_Adults_Only_games_says_ESRBs_Vance.php|archive-date=2014-11-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"polygon-aoartform\">{{cite web|title=Why the Adults Only rating may be pointless and harmful to games as an art form|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/10/5362502/adults-only-rating-pointless-and-harmful-games-as-art-form|work=Polygon|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=March 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403164014/http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/10/5362502/adults-only-rating-pointless-and-harmful-games-as-art-form|archive-date=2014-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/10/5397680/the-cold-war-on-the-ao-rating-must-stop-if-gaming-is-to-grow-up|title=The cold war on the Adults Only rating must stop if gaming is to grow up|date=February 20, 2014|last=Kuchera|first=Ben|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=September 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007173116/http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/10/5397680/the-cold-war-on-the-ao-rating-must-stop-if-gaming-is-to-grow-up|archive-date=2014-10-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"polygon-mutedviolence\">{{cite web|title=A history of (muted) violence|url=http://www.polygon.com/features/2013/8/8/4595050/adults-only-ao-games|work=Polygon|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=March 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322224633/http://www.polygon.com/features/2013/8/8/4595050/adults-only-ao-games|archive-date=2014-03-22|url-status=live}}</ref> The release of ''[[Thrill Kill]]'', an AO-rated fighting game with strong sexual themes, was outright cancelled by [[Electronic Arts]] (who had acquired its developer) due to objections over its content.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-512347.html |title=EA kills 'Thrill Kill' game before release |work=[[ZDNet]] |date=October 15, 1998 |accessdate=December 18, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116223732/http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-512347.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=November 16, 2006}}</ref> Following the discovery of an [[Hot Coffee mod|incomplete sex minigame]] that was not included in the final game but could be accessed using a [[game mod|modification]] or cheating device, ''[[Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas]]'' was re-rated Adults Only and recalled by [[Rockstar Games]], in favor of a new revision of the game that omitted the offending content entirely and carried the original Mature rating.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4702737.stm |title=Hidden sex scenes hit GTA rating |work=BBC News |date=July 21, 2005 |accessdate=December 18, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061224002226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4702737.stm |archive-date=2006-12-24 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"RerateToAORating\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6129500.html | title = San Andreas rated AO, Take-Two suspends production | work = [[GameSpot]] | publisher = [[CNET Networks]] | accessdate = July 1, 2006 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060203013156/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6129500.html | archive-date = 2006-02-03 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\"RevertToMRating\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6152490.html |title=FTC Hot Coffee ruling scalds, but doesn't burn Take-Two |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=CNET Networks |accessdate=July 1, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708231006/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6152490.html |archivedate=July 8, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Venezuela==\nIn November 2009, the Government of [[Venezuela]] announced that it would ban all video games in which the objective was to shoot people. The ban was due to widespread violence in the country.\n\nThe bill was later published in the public journal of that country on December 3<ref>http://www.tsj.gov.ve/gaceta/Diciembre/3122009/3122009.pdf#page=2 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331052830/http://www.tsj.gov.ve/gaceta/Diciembre/3122009/3122009.pdf |date=2010-03-31 }}</ref> and went into effect 3 months later,<ref>[http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/145976/hoy-entra-en-vigencia-ley-que-prohibe-video-juegos-y-juguetes-belico/ Hoy entra en vigencia ley que prohibe videojuegos y juguetes b\u00e9licos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508014255/http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/145976/hoy-entra-en-vigencia-ley-que-prohibe-video-juegos-y-juguetes-belico/ |date=2010-05-08 }}. Noticias24. Retrieved 2010-06-08.</ref> March 3, 2010, making Venezuela the first country to completely ban violent video games in the world and make their manufacturing, distribution, selling, rental, exhibition and use illegal. Even though the proponents were not from the Venezuelan Government's political party, [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela|Partido Socialista Unido de Venezuela (PSUV)]], President [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] supported the ban,<ref>[http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/139787/chavez-la-emprende-de-nuevo-contra-la-muneca-barbie-y-la-play-station/ Ch\u00e1vez la emprende de nuevo contra la mu\u00f1eca \"Barbie\" y la \"Play Station\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406011717/http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/139787/chavez-la-emprende-de-nuevo-contra-la-muneca-barbie-y-la-play-station/ |date=2010-04-06 }}. Noticias24. Retrieved 2010-06-08.</ref> claiming there are some Internet games featuring him so players can \"kill them\"; and even calling video games consoles, including Nintendo DS and Sony PlayStation, \"poison\" and values of capitalism, which he considers \"the road to hell\".\n\nAccording to reports of the Venezuelan National Guard, more than 13,000 objects, including violent video games, have been massively destroyed in the states of Lara<ref>[http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/153107/gnb-destruyo-5-mil-600-juguetes-belicos-en-lara/ GNB destruy\u00f3 5 mil 600 juguetes b\u00e9licos en Lara] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618120255/http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/153107/gnb-destruyo-5-mil-600-juguetes-belicos-en-lara/ |date=2010-06-18 }}. Noticias24. Retrieved 2010-06-08.</ref> and Portuguesa.<ref>{{cite web |author=Foto: Prensa Core4 |url=http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/158256/en-fotos-gnb-destruye-juguetes-y-videojuegos-belicos-en-portuguesa/ |title=En fotos: GNB destruye juguetes y videojuegos b\u00e9licos en Portuguesa |publisher=Noticias24.com |accessdate=2011-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001080349/http://www.noticias24.com/actualidad/noticia/158256/en-fotos-gnb-destruye-juguetes-y-videojuegos-belicos-en-portuguesa/ |archive-date=2011-10-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe ban is criticized by gamers and experts alike for its ambiguity and lack of clarity on its penalties, aside from being too harsh and indoctrinating a negative point of view.<ref>Inside Telecom Vol. V #85, Secci\u00f3n Agenda. 2009-11-16.</ref> On the other hand, Sony expressed their hopes for the government to make changes for the law for good.<ref>[http://www.hormigaanalitica.com/innovaciones/gow.htm Cultores de God of War III esperan ayuda del Olimpo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328121220/http://hormigaanalitica.com/innovaciones/gow.htm |date=2010-03-28 }}. Hormiga Anal\u00edtica. Retrieved 2010-06-08.</ref>\n\nThe ban extends to the digital versions of these games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/|title=Welcome to Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719232818/http://store.steampowered.com/|archive-date=2017-07-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Vietnam==\nMegaman 5 is believed to be banned in Vietnam, due to one of the boss, Napalm Man, as well as the stage itself, refers to the [[Vietnam War]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Video game controversy]]\n* [[List of regionally censored video games]]\n* [[List of recalled video games]]\n* [[List of banned films]]\n* [[List of books banned by governments]]\n* [[List of controversial video games]]\n{{inc-vg}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n{{Censorship}}\n{{Video game controversy}}\n{{Law country lists}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banned Video Games}}\n[[Category:Video game lists by reception or rating|Banned computer and video games]]\n[[Category:Censored video games|*]]\n[[Category:Blacklisting|Video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{More citations needed|list|date=September 2010}}\n\nThis is a '''list of [[video game]]s that have been [[censorship|censored]] or [[ban (law)|banned]]''' by [[government]]s of various [[Jurisdiction (area)|states]] in the world. Governments that have banned video games have been criticized for a correlated increase in digital [[copyright infringement|piracy]], limiting business opportunities and violating rights.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/29/arts/video-games/what-supreme-court-ruling-on-video-games-means.html?_r=0|title=Supreme Court Has Ruled; Now Games Have a Duty|last1=Schiesel|first1=Seth|date=2011-06-28|website=The New York Times|accessdate=2014-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523015748/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/29/arts/video-games/what-supreme-court-ruling-on-video-games-means.html?_r=0|archive-date=2014-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court-strikes-calif-law-banning-sale-of-violent-video-games-to-minors/2011/06/26/AGwtxenH_story.html|title=Supreme Court strikes Calif. law banning sale of violent video games to minors|last1=Barnes|first1=Robert|date=2011-06-27|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=2014-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529120554/http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court-strikes-calif-law-banning-sale-of-violent-video-games-to-minors/2011/06/26/AGwtxenH_story.html|archive-date=2014-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/06/27/supreme-court-violent-video-games_n_884991.html|title=Supreme Court Violent Video Games Ruling: Ban On Sale, Rental To Children Unconstitutional|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=2011-06-27|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=2014-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522105214/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/06/27/supreme-court-violent-video-games_n_884991.html|archive-date=2014-05-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{TOCright|80}}\n\n==Afghanistan==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|'''All'''\n|During the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan|five-year reign]] of the [[Taliban]] government in Afghanistan, Western technology and art was prohibited and this included ''all'' video games.\n|}\n\n==Argentina==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Carmageddon]]''\n|Banned in the city of [[Buenos Aires]] because it depicts people being killed by motor vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ley 16 - Juego Electr\u00f3nico \"Carmaggedon\" y similares - Prohibici\u00f3n |url=http://www2.cedom.gob.ar/es/legislacion/normas/leyes/ley16.html |website=Direccion General Centro Documental de Informaci\u00f3n y Archivo Legislativo |accessdate=29 July 2018 |location=Hip\u00f3lito Yrigoyen 502, Buenos Aires, Argentina |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729052850/http://www2.cedom.gob.ar/es/legislacion/normas/leyes/ley16.html |archive-date=2018-07-29 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[RapeLay]]''\n| Banned because the object of the game is to stalk and rape a woman and her two daughters, at least one of whom appears to be underage.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1255814-breves |title=Breves \u2013 Alertan por el riesgo de un videojuego |date=19 April 2010 |access-date=30 July 2018 |work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]] |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730203250/https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1255814-breves |archive-date=2018-07-30 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5520973/years-later-argentina-bans-rape-video-game|title=Years Later, Argentina Bans Rape Video Game|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Brian|date=21 April 2010|website=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=30 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730234744/https://kotaku.com/5520973/years-later-argentina-bans-rape-video-game|archive-date=2018-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Australia==\n{{Main|List of banned video games in Australia}}\n\n==Brazil==\n{{main|Video gaming in Brazil}}\n\nBrazil has banned many video games since 1999, mainly due to depictions of violence and cruelty,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/2447352.html |title=Brazil Bans More Games |last1=Mullen |first1=Michael |date=1999-12-17 |website=GameSpot |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203140923/http://www.gamespot.com/news/2447352.html |archivedate=2010-12-03 }}</ref> making it illegal to distribute and otherwise sell these games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.normasbrasil.com.br/norma/portaria-724-1999_181386.html|title=Portaria MJ n\u00ba 724 de 16/12/1999|date=1999-12-17|website=Normas Brasil|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401212938/http://www.normasbrasil.com.br/norma/portaria-724-1999_181386.html|archive-date=2018-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mprs.mp.br/noticias/id13845.htm|title=Proibida venda de jogo eletr\u00f4nico|date=1999-04-08|website=MPRS|access-date=2018-10-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052954/http://www.mprs.mp.br/noticias/id13845.htm|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Bully (video game)|Bully]]''\n| Banned for showing violence and harassment in a school setting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/brazil-judge-bans-video-game-bully-1.288552|title=Brazil Judge Bans Video Game 'Bully'|date=2011-04-11|website=CTVNews|accessdate=2016-05-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625081417/http://www.ctvnews.ca/brazil-judge-bans-video-game-bully-1.288552|archive-date=2016-06-25|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was lifted on 23 June 2016; the game can now be acquired in physical and non-physical format through [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/12200/Bully_Scholarship_Edition/?cc=br|title=Bully: Scholarship Edition on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Counter-Strike (video game)|Counter-Strike]]''\n| Banned because of violence and simulating a favela map in 2008. The ban was later lifted and the game is now available for sale.<ref name=\"CVGCounterstrike\">{{cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/179980/banned-in-brazil-counter-strike-and-everquest/|title=Banned in Brazil: Counter-Strike and EverQuest|last1=Bishop|first1=Stuart|date=2008-01-21|website=CVG|accessdate=2014-07-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008114605/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/179980/banned-in-brazil-counter-strike-and-everquest/|archive-date=2014-10-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Do G1, em S\u00e3o Paulo |url=http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Games/0,,MUL1199747-9666,00-JUSTICA+LIBERA+VENDA+DO+GAME+COUNTERSTRIKE+NO+BRASIL.html |title=G1 - Games - Justi\u00e7a libera venda do game 'Counter-Strike' no Brasil |language=Portuguese |date=2008-06-18 |publisher=G1.globo.com |accessdate=2011-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006091104/http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Games/0%2C%2CMUL1199747-9666%2C00-JUSTICA%2BLIBERA%2BVENDA%2BDO%2BGAME%2BCOUNTERSTRIKE%2BNO%2BBRASIL.html |archive-date=2011-10-06 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[EverQuest]]''\n| Banned because of Australia's X18+ references.<ref name=\"CVGCounterstrike\"/><ref name=\"brazil bans fun\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/346800/brazilian-government-bans-counter+strike-everquest-fun |title=Only in Brazil: Brazilian Government Bans Counter-Strike, EverQuest, Fun |date=2008-01-18 |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |website=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=2014-07-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080427094758/http://kotaku.com/346800/brazilian-government-bans-counter%2Bstrike-everquest-fun |archivedate=April 27, 2008 }}</ref> The ban has been mostly lifted since 2009, except in [[Minas Gerais]].\n|-\n| ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Episodes from Liberty City]]''\n| Banned in [[Barueri]] because it uses music by the Brazilian composer Hamilton da Silva Louren\u00e7o without proper permission.<ref name=\"Brazil bans GTA4:LCS\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5666949/brazilian-court-forbids-the-sale-of-episodes-from-liberty-city-worldwide|title=Brazilian Court Forbids The Sale Of Episodes From Liberty City Worldwide|last1=Bueno|first1=Renato|date=2010-10-18|website=Kotaku|accessdate=2014-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720102047/http://kotaku.com/5666949/brazilian-court-forbids-the-sale-of-episodes-from-liberty-city-worldwide|archive-date=2014-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref> It has been resolved and was lifted in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/12220/Grand_Theft_Auto_Episodes_from_Liberty_City/?cc=br|title=Grand Theft Auto: Episodes from Liberty City on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818031349/http://store.steampowered.com/app/12220/Grand_Theft_Auto_Episodes_from_Liberty_City/?cc=br|archive-date=2017-08-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\nAdditionally, the [[Brazilian advisory rating system]] requires that all video games be rated by the organization, where unrated video games are banned from being sold in Brazil. Often, bans do not extend to digital platforms.\n\n==China==\nA very large number of video games are banned in the People's Republic of China. Games that depict drugs, sexual themes, blood, organized crime or defamation of the Chinese government are almost always banned. Because of the large size of the Chinese video game market, many studios edit the content of their games to conform to the government's standards.\n\nHome gaming consoles were banned in mainland China from June 2000<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/gaming/gaming-news/lenovos-kinect-clone-evades-chinese-ban-on-video-game-consoles/article4104133/|title=Lenovo's Kinect-clone evades Chinese ban on video-game consoles|last=Hook|first=Leslie|date=2012-06-18|accessdate=2012-08-20|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608053047/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/gaming/gaming-news/lenovos-kinect-clone-evades-chinese-ban-on-video-game-consoles/article4104133/|archive-date=2012-06-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/features/9263-Console-Revolution|title=Console Revolution|last=Ume|first=Luke|date=2011-12-15|accessdate=2012-08-20|work=The Escapist|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512170149/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/features/9263-Console-Revolution|archive-date=2012-05-12|url-status=live}}</ref> until 2013; when the ban was lifted, [[Eighth generation console|next-generation consoles]] such as the [[Xbox One]] and [[PlayStation 4]] were allowed in the country.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jou|first=Eric|title=China Lifts Their Console Ban... But With Strings Attached|url=http://kotaku.com/china-lifts-their-console-ban-but-theres-strings-at-1425338783|website=Kotaku|accessdate=September 30, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930103446/http://kotaku.com/china-lifts-their-console-ban-but-theres-strings-at-1425338783|archive-date=2013-09-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2019, after implementing a new mandatory local rating and approval system, any and all games containing depictions of violence, blood, gambling and imperial history are ''de facto'' banned from all accessible platforms in the nation (unless otherwise changed to comply with local standards).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/04/22/china-gaming-rules-gambling-blood/|title=China's new gaming rules prohibit blood and gambling|website=Engadget|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504070630/https://www.engadget.com/2019/04/22/china-gaming-rules-gambling-blood/|archive-date=2019-05-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/gaming/news/china-game-approvals-1203194653/|title=China Introduces New Game Approval Process This Month|last=Fogel|first=Stefanie|last2=Fogel|first2=Stefanie|date=2019-04-22|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504070628/https://variety.com/2019/gaming/news/china-game-approvals-1203194653/|archive-date=2019-05-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://china-underground.com/2019/04/22/china-gaming-rules/|title=China's new gaming rules ban blood, gambling and some games based on the Chinese imperial past|date=2019-04-22|website=China Underground|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514194521/https://china-underground.com/2019/04/22/china-gaming-rules/|archive-date=2019-05-14|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=June 2019}}{{dubious|China|date=June 2019 }}\n\nNotable games banned in this region are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n| ''[[Battlefield 4]]''\n| Banned for discrediting China's national image as well as threatening national security. The Chinese Ministry claims that the game shows a \"cultural invasion\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/battlefield-china-banned-illegal-shooter,25542.html |title=Battlefield 4 Now Banned in China|last1=Parrish|first1=Kevin|date=2013-12-27|website=Tom's Hardware|accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Command & Conquer Generals]]''\n| Banned for \"smearing the image of China and the Chinese army\", although the game presents China as a protagonist and glorifies the People's Liberation Army.<ref name=\"swede game\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-05/29/content_334845.htm|title=Swedish video game banned for harming China's sovereignty|date=2004-05-29|publisher=Xinhua|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426235535/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-05/29/content_334845.htm|archive-date=2014-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref>  Additionally, the China campaign has the player destroy questionable targets such as the [[Three Gorges Dam]] and the [[Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre]] in order to snuff out an invading terrorist organization.\n|-\n| ''[[Football Manager 2005]]''\n| Banned for recognizing [[Taiwan]] and [[Tibet]] as independent countries. An edited version was later released globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-12/08/content_398445.htm|title=China bans online game Football Manager 2005|date=2004-12-08|publisher=Xinhua|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728041944/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-12/08/content_398445.htm|archive-date=2014-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[I.G.I.-2: Covert Strike]]''\n| Banned because of \"intentionally blackening China and the Chinese army's image\".<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-03/19/content_316379.htm|title= Computer game cracked down on for discrediting China's image|date= 2004-03-19|publisher= Xinhua|access-date= 2007-03-13|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070405120258/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-03/19/content_316379.htm|archive-date= 2007-04-05|url-status= live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[RapeLay]]''\n|Banned because it \"tends to promote and support the use of violence to compel a person to submit to sexual conduct, and the exploitation of young persons for sexual purposes\".{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n|-\n| ''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n|Banned because of sexual content and glorifying homosexuality.{{citation_needed|date=June 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Devotion (video game)|Devotion]]''\n|Banned due to an easter egg insulting [[Xi Jinping]], who is the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]]. The easter egg was later removed, but the game remains banned. On February 21, players discovered a ''[[fulu]]'' talisman decorating a wall in the game contained the words \"[[Xi Jinping]] [[Winnie-the-Pooh]]\" ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u5c0f\u718a\u7dad\u5c3c) in Chinese [[seal script]], referencing a recent Chinese [[internet meme]] that compared the Chinese [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|general secretary]] to the [[Winnie the Pooh (Disney character)|Disney character]].\n|-\n| ''[[Plague Inc.]]/[[Plague Inc. Evolved]]''\n|Banned in China as a result of the ongoing [[2019-2020 coronavirus outbreak|coronavirus outbreak]] that had originated in the mainland and had spread to other countries. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://steamcommunity.com/games/plagueincevolved/announcements/detail/1723128189771746868|title= Plague Inc. banned in China|date= 2020-03-02|publisher=Steam|accessdate=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n|}\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games is banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\n==Cuba==\n{{see also|Censorship in Cuba}}\nNo video games have ever been banned in Cuba, but few games were sold in that country until 2007 when restrictions were eased. In 2010, the video game ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops]]'' generated a lot of controversy as there is a mission where the player attempts to assassinate [[Fidel Castro]], only to end up killing a double.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1328719/Call-Duty-Black-Ops-Fidel-Castro-plot-causes-outrage-Cuba.html?ITO=1490 | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Call of Duty: Black Ops plot allowing players to assassinate Fidel Castro causes outrage in Cuba | date=2010-11-11 | access-date=2010-11-11 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114012919/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1328719/Call-Duty-Black-Ops-Fidel-Castro-plot-causes-outrage-Cuba.html?ITO=1490 | archive-date=2010-11-14 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Denmark==\n''[[EA Sports MMA]]'' was not released in Denmark because of a law prohibiting marketing for energy drinks, which EA chose not to remove from the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/sports-mma-releasing-denmark |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140717220008/http://www.1up.com/news/sports-mma-releasing-denmark |url-status=dead |archive-date=2014-07-17 |title=EA Sports MMA Not Releasing in Denmark |last1=Pereira |first1=Chris |date=2008-09-30 |website=1up.com |accessdate=2014-11-25 }}</ref> However, distribution is not illegal, as the game can still be found on shelves as an import.\n\n==Germany==\n{{main|Video gaming in Germany}}\n\nA [[video game]] can be banned in [[Germany]] if it is confiscated by court order because it violates a section of the [[Strafgesetzbuch]] (criminal code). Private possession (and thus playing it) and acquisition (such as downloading a demo from the Internet) are still legal, but any [[wikt:dissemination|dissemination]] is not. The seller would break the law if a sale took place, not the buyer. However, on December 10, 2002, one German court (Oberlandesgericht [[Hamm]]) decided that a single sale of a single copy does not qualify as dissemination.<ref>''[http://www.medienzensur.de/seite/beschlagnahmung.shtml Beschlagnahmung] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514233525/http://www.medienzensur.de/seite/beschlagnahmung.shtml |date=2007-05-14 }}'', medienzensur.de</ref> Unlike indexing by the [[Bundespr\u00fcfstelle f\u00fcr jugendgef\u00e4hrdende Medien|BPjM]], which restricts the sale of all content-equal versions, the versions that are confiscated are enumerated in the court order. Being put on the index by the BPjM or, since April 1, 2003, being refused a rating by the [[Unterhaltungssoftware Selbstkontrolle|USK]], does not equal a ban. Rather, it imposes strict trade restrictions on the title. While only very few games have been confiscated, the list of indexed games is very long.<ref>''[http://www.cybercafe-software.com/indexlist.html Software for your Internet Cafe - Computer Games on the Index List] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730041247/http://www.cybercafe-software.com/indexlist.html |date=2013-07-30 }}'', InterCafe</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, just one month after the [[Emsdetten school shooting]], [[Bavaria]] and [[Lower Saxony]] proposed legislation, to be presented to the national parliament, that would make even playing any game that featured \u201ccruel violence on humans or human-looking characters\u201d punishable by fines and up to a year in prison.    \n<ref>''[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/e98b3a9a-851c-11db-b12c-0000779e2340.html Germany to crack down on violent video games] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819095834/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/e98b3a9a-851c-11db-b12c-0000779e2340.html |date=2007-08-19 }}'' by Bertrand Benoit, 2006-12-06.</ref><ref>[http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=12002 Germany Drafts Stringent Anti-Violent Game Law] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012102334/http://gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=12002 |date=2007-10-12 }} by Jason Dobson, [[Gamasutra]], 2006-12-06.</ref><ref>[http://uk.gamespot.com/news/6163059.html?tag=latestnews;title;1 German gov't considers jail time for gamers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226011908/http://uk.gamespot.com/news/6163059.html?tag=latestnews%3Btitle%3B1 |date=2009-02-26 }} by Emma Boyes, [[GameSpot]] UK, December 2006.</ref>\n\n[[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|\u00a7 86a]] outlaws the use of symbols of unconstitutional organisations, \u00a7 130 [[Volksverhetzung]] (agitation of the people), and \u00a7 131 instructions for committing crimes. In the official lists, these three sections are always bundled, so any game that contains [[swastika flag]]s and/or any depiction of [[Adolf Hitler]] is listed alongside racist propaganda pieces. This law was lifted on August 8, 2018.\n\n\u00a7 131 outlaws representation of excessive violence in media \"which describe cruel or otherwise inhuman acts of violence against human or humanoid beings in a manner which expresses a glorification or rendering harmless of such acts of violence or which represents the cruel or inhuman aspects of the event in a manner which injures [[dignity|human dignity]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iuscomp.org/gla/statutes/StGB.htm#131 |title=German Criminal Code, Section 131 Representation of Violence |publisher=Iuscomp.org |accessdate=2011-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008212200/http://www.iuscomp.org/gla/statutes/StGB.htm#131 |archive-date=2011-10-08 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\u00a7 130 and \u00a7 131 make it a criminal offence to do the following with corresponding scriptures:\n\n# distribute/sell them\n# issue in public, demonstrate or otherwise make them available\n# leave them to a person under the age of 18\n# produce, buy, deliver, store, offer, announce, praise, import or export them within the meaning of points 1 to 3.\n\nThis means that import or purchase and possession for personal use of such games is still legal for persons over 18 years of age.\n\nIn the case of video games that contain pornography with children or minors, where a real or realistic event is depicted, the possession of the video game or working towards possessing it would be illegal under \u00a7 184b or \u00a7184c StGB. Otherwise, if the work depicts a fictitious event, the distribution of such material is illegal.\n\nIn August 2008, [[Sega]] confirmed that ''[[The House of the Dead: Overkill]]'' and ''[[MadWorld]]'' would not be released in Germany,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoeverything.com/?p=2704|title=House of the Dead: Overkill and MadWorld banned from Germany|author=Brian|date=2008-08-19|website=nintendoeverything.com|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305044243/http://www.nintendoeverything.com/?p=2704|archive-date=2012-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref> due to the likelihood that they would be refused to get a rating by the USK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nintendo-online.de/wii/news/2312/house-of-the-dead-overkill-madworld-nicht-in-deutschland/|title=House of the Dead: Overkill & MadWorld nicht in Deutschland!|last1=G.|first1=Philipp|date=2008-08-19|website=nintendo-online.de/|language=German|accessdate=2014-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719031819/http://nintendo-online.de/wii/news/2312/house-of-the-dead-overkill-madworld-nicht-in-deutschland/|archive-date=2014-07-19|url-status=live}}</ref> Sega also announced in November 2009 that they would not distribute ''[[Aliens vs. Predator]]'' for similar reasons.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2009/11/11/news-avpvgermany-sega-won-t-be-selling-game-to-germans.aspx|title=AvPvGermany? Sega Won't Be Selling Game To Germans|last=Pyle|first=Duke E.|magazine=[[Game Informer]]|date=2009-11-11|accessdate=2011-10-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603133619/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2009/11/11/news-avpvgermany-sega-won-t-be-selling-game-to-germans.aspx|archive-date=2012-06-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA \"Beschlagnahmung\" ([[Ban (law)|ban]]) is enforced for a minimum of ten years, after which a request for review may be submitted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/doom-sales-ban-doom-2-fps-ego-shooter,13353.html|title=Germany Removes Doom Sales Ban After 17 Years|last1=Perry|first1=Douglas|date=2011-09-04|website=Tom's Hardware|accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the bans usually don't extend to the digital versions, local versions are still toned down in depictions of violence and similar content to be classified by the USK without any rulings.\n\n<!-- The \"Reason\" column is ''very'' repetitive. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Reason\n|-\n|''[[10.000 Bullets]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[25 to Life]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[50 Cent: Blood on the Sand]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[50 Cent: Bulletproof]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[Afro Samurai (video game)|Afro Samurai]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[Aliens vs. Predator (2009 video game)|Aliens vs. Predator]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[Area 51 (2005 video game)|Area 51]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence. A censored version was released.\n|-\n|''[[Army of Two]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[Army of Two: The 40th Day]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[Army of Two: The Devil's Cartel]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[Beat Down: Fists of Vengeance]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.\n|-\n|''[[Bloodrayne]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence. A censored version was released. The banned, uncensored version, with Nazi references removed, was available on Steam and GOG without classification until it was taken down on May 31, 2016.\n|-\n|''[[Bloodrayne II]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence. A censored version was released. The banned, uncensored version was available on Steam and GOG without classification until it was taken 